To recreate the provided image using LaTeX and TikZ, you can use the following code. This code recreates the simple block diagram representing the computational model described:

```latex
\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{positioning}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=2cm, every node/.style={align=center}]
    % Input node
    \node (input) {$\vert \mathbf{f} \rangle$ \\ Inputs};

    % Machine node
    \node[draw, rectangle, minimum width=3cm, minimum height=2cm, right=of input] (machine) {$M(\mathbf{L})$};

    % Output node
    \node[right=of machine] (output) {$\mathbf{L} \vert \mathbf{f} \rangle = \vert \mathbf{f}' \rangle$ \\ Outputs};

    % Connect nodes with arrows
    \draw[->] (input) -- (machine);
    \draw[->] (machine) -- (output);
\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

### Explanation:
- **Nodes**: 
  - The `node` command is used to create blocks/texts. 
  - The input node `$\vert \mathbf{f} \rangle$ \\ Inputs` specifies the input section, with the line break (`\\`) used to stack "Inputs" below the mathematical symbol.
  - The machine node `M(\mathbf{L})` is depicted as a rectangle using the `draw` and `rectangle` options. It's placed to the right of the input node using the `positioning` library.
  - The output node is similar to the input node, displaying the transformed function.

- **Connections**:
  - Arrows are drawn from the input to the machine and from the machine to the output using the `\draw[->]` command.

This setup effectively replicates the structure and labels of the original image using TikZ in LaTeX.

